<section class="bg-white text-slate-900 py-20 lg:py-28 border-t border-slate-200">
  <div class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 max-w-5xl">

    <!-- Section header -->
    <div class="mb-14 text-center lg:text-left">
      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl lg:text-4xl font-semibold mb-4">
        Why most marketing efforts fail
      </h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-slate-600 max-w-2xl mx-auto lg:mx-0">
        Not because businesses don’t spend enough — but because they scale activity
        before understanding the financial logic behind acquisition.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Core reasons -->
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-10">
      
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-lg mb-2">
          Execution without financial context
        </h3>
        <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
          Ads, websites, and funnels are launched without knowing break-even,
          margin tolerance, or customer lifetime value.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-lg mb-2">
          Scaling tactics instead of systems
        </h3>
        <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
          Businesses double down on what “seems to work” without fixing routing,
          tracking, or follow-up.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-lg mb-2">
          Leads without qualification
        </h3>
        <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
          Volume replaces intent. Sales teams chase noise instead of predictable,
          qualified demand.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="font-medium text-lg mb-2">
          No ownership over the system
        </h3>
        <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
          When agencies leave, the knowledge leaves with them.
          The business is forced to start over.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>

    <!-- Closing line -->
    <div class="mt-16 border-t border-slate-200 pt-8">
      <p class="text-slate-700 max-w-3xl">
        Growth only becomes predictable when acquisition is treated as a system —
        not a collection of tactics.
      </p>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>
